										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="wp-block-paragraph">This artical we talk and discuss about the hot filling machine from its technology, construcion materials and Industrial Applications.It will help users to understand the hot filling and know how to choose a hot filling machine for their products.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">What is a hot filling machine?</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">A hot filling machine is type of filling and dosing equipment designed to fill liquids or semi-liquids into containers while the product is still heated. This work process is typically used for two main reasons: either to make the products easier to flow by heating it until it melts into liquid, or to ensure the product is sterile for longer shelf life. You’ll find hot filling machines commonly used for products like juices, sauce,butter or some type of honey, which require heat to prevent spoilage. They’re also essential for products such as candles, lip balms, lipstick,car wax, and petroleum-based goods, such as grease, also some chemicals, such as glue.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Hot Filling Technology</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Npack has been in construction filling machines for more than 15 years, we conclude the hot filling technology mainly used in two different ways, depending on whether the product is liquid or semi-solid.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><strong>1. Heat-for-Safety Filling (for liquids)</strong><br>This is the standard path for drinks, sauces, and similar food products. The goal is to sterilize and kill germs of the liquid and for a long shelf life without needing preservatives. The working process uses a powerful one-two punch: first, the liquid is sterilized at very high temperatures normally from 135°C to150°C to kill germs, and then it&#8217;s filled into containers while still piping hot(85–96°C). As it cools, it creates a vacuum seal, locking in safety and freshness. You&#8217;ll find this used for everything from bottled juices and iced tea to pasta sauces and drinkable yogurts. For food indusry , this technology is the most popular way. we can call this technology as thermal Sterilization Filling.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><strong>2. Heat-to-Fill Filling (for semi-solids)</strong><br>This way is for products that are solid at room temperature but must be melted when filling and package. Heating is used to carefully turn the product into a thick, pourable fluid liquid. Once filled into its final packaging containers (such as a lipstick tube or a grease cartridge), it cools back into its familiar solid form. This is essential for products like lipsticks, deodorants, petroleum jelly, industrial greases, and solid perfumes. we can call this technology as Melt-Phase Filling.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">While these heating filling systems solve different issues, they share one non-negotiable requirement:&nbsp;extremely precise control of temperature<strong>.</strong>&nbsp;Every step depends on getting the heat just right.</p>


